@node not7 "PETRO TYSCHTSCHENKO'S SAKU 98 SPEECH TRANSCRIPT IS NOW AVAILABLE."

@{FG Shine}@{I}PETRO TYSCHTSCHENKO @{UI}'S @{B}SAKU 98@{UB} SPEECH TRANSCRIPT IS NOW AVAILABLE@{FG Text}
----------------------------------------------------------------

@{FG Fill}DATE: 1998/04/06@{FG Text}

@{I}FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE @{UI}

ESPOO,  FINLAND  - April 2, 1998 - @{B}Saku 98@{UB}, organized by the @{B}Finnish Amiga Users
Group@{UB}  on March 28th in Vantaa, was visited by an estimated total of 500 people,
making  @{B}Saku  98@{B}  the  biggest @{B}Amiga@{UB} only event in Finland in years. Of the 500,
almost  250  visitors  were  listening  to  the  speech of @{B}Amiga International@{UB}'s
managing director, @{I}Petro Tyschtschenko. @{UI}

In  his  speech,  @{I}Mr.  Tyschtschenko @{UI}introduced himself to the Finnish audience,
announced the availability of cheap @{B}Amiga A1200@{UB} computers for user group members
and  launched  the  new  @{B}Amiga@{UB} hymn. After his speech, Mr.Tyschtschenko answered
some  questions  and  revealed  a  couple  of interesting details, including the
possibility  of  @{B}Netscape@{UB}  as part of future @{B}AmigaOS@{UB} upgrades. He also mentioned
the destiny of the remaining @{B}Walker@{UB} models.

The speech is now available at the @{B}Finnish Amiga Users Group@{UB}'s Web Site, both in
ASCII  text  and  MP3  audio.  The  direct  URL for the English @{B}Saku 98@{UB} pages is
@{B}http://batman.jytol.fi/~saku/saku98/english.html@{UB}   or   for   the   mirror  site
@{B}http://tzimmola.tky.hut.fi/saku/saku98/english.html@{UB}.  E-mail  inquiries  may  be
sent to @{I}Janne Siren (siren@mikrobitti.fi). @{UI}

@{I}About @{B}Finnish Amiga Users Group @{UB}@{UI}

@{B}Finnish  Amiga  Users  Group@{UB}  is  a  non-profit organization for promoting @{B}Amiga@{UB}
computing and helping @{B}Amiga@{UB} users in Finland. Also known as @{B}Saku@{UB}, after its disk
magazine, the group is trying to accomplish its goals by organizing meetings and
by publishing a disk magazine. Since 1993 the @{B}Finnish Amiga Users Group@{UB} and it's
predecessors  have  released  24  issues  of  the  disk  magazine  and held five
