@node not26 "USER REPRESENTATIVE ELECTION 98 - THE ELECTION PROCEDURES"

@{FG Shine}@{I}USER REPRESENTATIVE @{UI}ELECTION 98 - THE ELECTION PROCEDURES@{FG Text}
---------------------------------------------------------

@{FG Fill}DATE: 1998/04/30@{FG Text}

IN COOPERATION WITH THE @{B}JMS@{UB}, @{B}TEAM AMIGA WORLDWIDE@{UB}, and @{B}ICOA@{UB}

The  bylaws  of  the  @{B}Industry  Council  of Open Amiga@{UB} require that the @{B}Steering
Committee@{UB}  have  1  full  voting  seat  to  be occupied by a user representative
selected in the manner deemed by the @{B}ICOA@{UB} to be the most productive way in which
to provide a user representative.

Therefore,  the  @{B}Transitional  Steering  Committee@{UB}  (@{B}TSC@{UB})  of  the  @{B}ICOA@{UB} invited
proposals  from  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  community  at large on selection procedures for the
selection  of a @{I}User Representative. @{UI}The @{B}JMS@{UB} answered this invitation with a set
of  proposals  and procedures that were hampered by time restrictions not of its
making.

When  voting was verified, there were several votes disqualified due to being of
a   fraudulent   nature,   leaving   three  of  the  candidates  all  but  tied.
Consultations  between  the nominees, the @{B}JMS@{UB}, and @{B}Team AMIGA@{UB} made it clear that
corrective action needed to be taken.

Because of the time constraints, lack of proper publicity, and fraudulent votes,
The @{B}JMS@{UB} in conjunction with @{B}Team AMIGA@{UB} asked for and obtained permission to hold
a  new  vote  with ample time for publicity, nominations, and voting from a much
wider audience than previously attained.

Following  are  the  new procedures outlined to gain a wider voting audience. We
urge  each  of you to take advantage of this opportunity to nominate and elect a
@{I}User Representative @{UI}of your choice.

The  person  elected  will  serve  as your spokesperson in the building of a new
@{B}Amiga@{UB} future. Choose wisely, but choose ...

@{I}EMAIL NOMINATIONS @{UI}

All  nominations must be sent to @{B}JMS@{UB} member @{I}Andrew Bienhaus(accolon@ionline.net) @{UI}
by midnight before (GMT) 30th May, 1998.  Nominations MUST include the following
information:

 * The  full  name,  preferred  language,  phone number and email address of the
   nominee.
 * The  full names, preferred languages, phone numbers and email addresses of at
   least five supporters
 * A  statement  that  the  named  people accept the election procedures and the
   decisions of the arbitrators as outlined below.
 * An election statement of no more than 500 words of plain text or HTML for the
   @{B}JMS@{UB}  election  web  site  to publish on the nominee's behalf. A URL with more
   information would be most beneficial to the candidate.

The  @{B}JMS@{UB} reserves the right to reject any statement whose contents do not appear
to  be  legal for it to publish. Separate versions of the statement in different
languages may be provided and will be posted by the @{B}JMS@{UB} as stated above.

@{I}Andrew Bienhaus @{UI}will write or phone to the nominee and each of his supporters to
confirm that the persons named are in agreement with the nomination, using their
preferred  language  when  possible.  If  @{I}Andrew @{UI}does NOT receive an affirmative
response  from  each of the above named persons no later than midnight before 31
May, 1998, the nomination will be considered invalid.

@{I}POSTAL NOMINATIONS @{UI}

Postal  nominations  must  include  all  of the information as required by email
nominations, plus the following:

 * Signature  of the  candidate with either an email address or a postal address
   AND phone number
 * Email addresses or postal addresses AND a phone number and signature for each
   supporter

Postal nominations should be mailed to:
@{I}Andrew Bienhaus @{UI}
90 Farr Crescent
Cambridge
Ontario N3C 1R6
Canada

More addresses may be added at a later time and will posted when available.

The vote takers, arbiters, and the collector of nominations may not be nominated
and  are  not  allowed  to  support any nomination. @{B}ICOA@{UB} members and prospective
members  may not be nominated and no more than two supporters of any nominee may
be @{B}ICOA@{UB} members or prospective members.

The  list  of  valid  nominees  for  the  election, along with pointers to their
election statements, will be made available by the @{B}JMS@{UB} as soon as possible after
2 June, 1998.

@{I}VOTING PROCEDURE @{UI}

Votes  may  be  cast by regular mail, Fido Netmail, email, or via a web form and
must  be received between midnight before (GMT) 2 June, 1998 and midnight before
(GMT)  20  June  1998. All voters must give their name and a valid email address
and  may  not  cast more than one vote in the election process. If more than one
vote comes from the same voter, all votes from that voter, email address and any
subsequent  addresses  will  be  disqualified.  Vote  takers,  arbiters, and the
collector of nominations are not allowed to cast votes.

@{I}VOTING BY REGULAR MAIL @{UI}

Ballots  may  be  obtained  through several @{B}Amiga@{UB} magazines for voting by normal
postal  mail.  Postal ballots should be mailed to @{I}Andrew Bienhaus @{UI}at the address
listed above.

@{I}VOTING BY FIDONET @{UI}

Persons  wishing  to  vote  from  Fidonet  @{B}Amiga@{UB} will forward a Netmail to @{I}Asha 
Develder, @{UI} moderator  at 1:202/720.5 and request a prenumbered ballot. @{I}Asha @{UI}will
return  by regular Fido netmail, a prenumbered ballot to the requester. Once the
ballot  has  been  completed,  this ballot will be returned to @{I}Asha Develder @{UI}for
verification.  Voted  Netmail  Addresses  will be posted to a listing on Fidonet
@{B}Amiga@{UB}  on a weekly basis by the moderator. Ballots will be forwarded to @{I}Andrew 
Bienhaus @{UI}no later than 20 June 1998.

@{I}VOTING BY INTERNET EMAIL @{UI}

An  official  ballot form will be made available once the list of candidates has
been  finalized.  All  votes by Internet Email must be made using this form with
only  one candidate selected. They must be forwarded to the official vote takers
email  address which will be announced at the time the ballot is made available.
Once the ballot is received by the vote taker, the vote taker will write back to
the  return address to confirm the vote. If the confirmation message is rejected
due to an invalid email address, the vote will not be counted.

@{I}VOTING BY WEB FORM @{UI}

Two  voting  forms  will  be  made  available on this web site during the voting
period. Voters must submit their email address on the first form in order to get
a  unique  key  sent  to them by email. The key will then be used to cast a vote
from the second form.

@{I}ANNOUNCEMENT OF RESULTS @{UI}

The  @{B}JMS@{UB}, @{B}Team AMIGA@{UB}, and the @{B}ICOA@{UB} together will arrange to announce the results
of  the election as soon as possible after the close of voting. This is expected
to be on 22 June or shortly thereafter.

@{I}COMPLAINTS PROCEDURE @{UI}

Anyone  who  feels  that this election is not being conducted fairly may make an
official complaint by writing to either @{I}Andrew Elia (andrew@amigasoc.org) @{UI}of the
@{B}Amiga  Society@{UB}  in London or @{I}Gary Peake (gpeake@wt.net) @{UI}of @{B}Team AMIGA@{UB}. They will
decide  if  the  complaint  is  justified  and, if so, what must be done to make
things  right. The @{B}JMS@{UB}, @{B}Team AMIGA@{UB}, and the @{B}ICOA@{UB} disclaim all responsibility for
disruption  in  the election procedures due to failures in the network or in the
equipment used by their service providers.

